default4.1
default 
defaultThe research 
defaultmodelled a range of plausible responses to the 
defaultreforms, based on housing and employment data and recent research on behavioural responses to the reforms to date. In their relatively generous central scenario CESI estimated that 155,000 claimants, of the 1.18 million out of work, may mitiga
defaultte their loss
defaultes by finding work;
default and 115,000 by moving home.  So in total, they estimated that 270,000 claimants – 23 per cent of the total impacted – may be successful in taking steps to mitigate the impacts of reform. This leaves a significant number of households an
defaultd individuals needing additional interim and long-term support with managing their money.
default&#xa0;
default4.2
default 
defaultThe establishment of the local authority-led Universal Credit face-to-face pilots in autumn 2012 recognised the LGA’s shared understanding with DWP that many of those who are affected by the welfare reforms will continue to look to councils and the volunta
defaultry sector as their principal source of advice and support. 
defaultThe pilots are helping to identify the challenges that councils and partners will face and, most importantly, developing practical solutions that other councils can learn from.
default&#xa0;
default4.3
default 
defaultT
defaulthis kind of suppor
defaultt can only be commissioned and delivered effectively through local partners who have an understanding of the local area, existing relationships with individuals and families and, in the vast majority of areas, an established track record in working togethe
defaultr to meet complex or multiple needs.
default&#xa0;
defaultLewisham – Universal Credit face-to-face supportdefault&#xa0;
defaultLewisham developed an approach for working with vulnerable residents that integrated preparation for the benefit cap with preparation for U
defaultniversal 
defaultC
defaultredit
default.
default&#xa0;
default A pilot te
defaultam was set up comprising officers from the council’s housing benefit and housing needs teams and Jobcentre Plus to design and then deliver the service. 
default&#xa0;
defaultPhase 1defaultA letter is sent to the customer explaining the key welfare changes and providing them with an
default estimate of the financial loss of the benefit cap.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe customer is contacted for a triage assessment over the phone, which 
defaultfocuses on skills and experience across the financial, digital, housing and employment spheres. The script built into Lewisham’s CR
defaultM system assigns scores to the answers given by the customer, which determines if they are considered ‘vulnerable’ triggering the need for a further support appointment. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA face-to-face appointment is conducted, focusing on the financial impact of the ben
defaultefit cap and returning to work after the cap.
default&#xa0;
defaultAn individualised support plan is created with warm referrals to key agencies who will be responsible for providing on-going support tailored to the individual needs identified. 
default&#xa0;
defaultPhase 2 defaultLewisham are working
default with the Behavioural Insights Team from the Cabinet Office to develop a case management approach which will see the team offering some customers more on
default&#xad;
defaultgoing support.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe project governance established to oversee the pilot meets monthly and has represen
defaulttation from all key local authority departments, VCS leads, JobCentre Plus and Housing associations. Working groups have been established representing the same areas but at an operational level.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen making referrals for clients as part of their support p
defaultlan the key partners the council has worked with are:
default&#xa0;
defaultfinancialdefault: Credit Union for budgeting accounts, CAB for debt/money management
default&#xa0;
defaultemploymentdefault: JCP (universal jobs match/ flexible support fund) and Lewisham’s Family Budget programme which is part of thei
defaultr Troubled Families initiative
default&#xa0;
defaulthousingdefault: referrals to Lewisham’s Housing Options Service
default&#xa0;
defaultdigitaldefault: customers are directed to where they can access the internet (local libraries and so on) and sites where they can access IT training. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is the council’s v
defaultiew that integrating housing and employment into local models is critical for the success of its approaches. Face-to-face triage makes it easier to identify those who are likely to need on-going support. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultCommunity Budgets defaultEssex, Greater Manchester, Wes
defaultt Cheshire and the London Tri-borough (Hammersmith &amp; Fulham, Kensington and Chelsea and Westminster) piloted a new approach to local public service transformation during 2012. In each of the four areas a range of partners, including NHS Trusts, the police,
default Jobcentre Plus, councils, the voluntary and private sectors and educational establishments worked together. The pilots demonstrated the benefits of aligning resources, reducing duplication and sharing information 
defaultthrough working together to break down pub
defaultlic, voluntary and independent sector boundaries and joining-up related, but disconnected delivery silos. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis model of collaborative leadership around the needs of a place is potentially very well-suited to helping customers affected by the welfare refo
defaultrms and commissioning local support services for Universal Credit.  The LGA is working closely with DWP and colleagues across local and national Government to ensure that the learning from Community Budgets is fed into the development and roll-out of Unive
defaultrsal Credit.
