default5.1
default 
defaultResearch on responses to the reforms to date shows relatively little evidence of claimants moving to more affordable accommodation. This is largely because cheaper accommodation simply isn’t available in the places that people want 
defaultto live and, crucially, work.
default Poor or insecure housing can also prevent people from being reliable and motivated to work
default and councils are ideally placed to ensure that housing and employment support is joined-up around the needs of people and families.
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default 
defaultTh
defaulte only way to ensure the 
defaultG
defaultovernment’s benefit reforms work is to address the 
defaultsignificant 
defaultundersupply
default of affordable housing and to support a more flexible supply of smaller properties to meet demand. This means that councils need to be free to invest in new
default homes that meet this need.
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default 
defaultHousing need has never been met by the private sector alone. Local Authorities and Housing Associations have an important role to play to increase the availability of housing of the right size and at the right price to meet 
defaultdemand. However, as of June 2013 Housin
defaultg Associations had completed 25 per cent
default fewer pr
defaultoperties than in the previous twelve
default months
default.
default Councils’ ability to build is limited by centrally set borrowing caps meaning build rates are depressed below their potent
defaultial levels.
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default 
defaultRemoving the H
defaultousing 
defaultR
defaultevenue 
defaultA
defaultccount
default borrowing cap could result in up to a further 60,000 homes over and above current plans. Overall 
defaultthe LGA 
defaultestimate that unlocking this potential to invest in housing would lead to a wider economic impact o
defaultf £20 billion
default.
default 
default 
defaultThe centrally set cap is distributed unevenly and bears little relation to overall housing need. This means some authorities have little or no borrowing headroom to invest in the smaller properties they need to meet demand.
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default 
defaultThe LGA will c
defaultontinue to press Government for to lift the borrowing cap and to trade borrowing headroom to allow greater investment in new affordable housing.
default&#xa0;
default5.6
default 
defaultCouncils are taking a range of approaches to use their existing stock more effectively and to incentivise peop
defaultle to move. All of those councils who are offering financial incentives to tenants to move into smaller 
defaulthomes have calculated that is will save them more in reduced rent arrears than it costs to pay the incentives.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultShropshire Council – supporting tenantsdefault through effective partnershipdefaultShropshire is one of the Housing Benefit Direct Payment Demonstration Projects.  The council has put a particular focus on working in partnership with the voluntary sector and has developed a financial inclusion board that in
defaultcludes housing associations, CAB, the Jobcentre Plus and other local support organisations to enable financial inclusion for tenants. Some of the services provided are signposting support, financial training and support for tenants, assistance with budgeti
defaultng to help them pay their rent, provision of banking facilities via credit unions and advice on basic bank accounts. Provision of case work and advocacy support is also available if required following a segmentation of residents in terms of capability. 
defaultTh
defaulte partners are evaluating tenants’ capability at a pre-tenancy stage as a way to sustain tenancies. Supporting tenants and identifying individuals requiring safeguarding of rent payments will be key to protecting landlords’ income streams. In Shropshire a 
defaulttrigger of 12 weeks is being tested before direct payment switches back to the landlord when the tenant hasn’t paid rent. Timely monitoring of rent arrears and intervention as well as signposting tenants to support as necessary are another key aspect of th
defaulteir work
default.
default5.7
default 
defaultDiscretionary Housing Paymentdefault&#xa0;
default5.7.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default£155 million has been made available to local authorities in Discretionary Housing Payments (DHPs) in 2013/14, to provide discretionary support to Housing Benefit claimants impacted by welfare reforms.  Our researc
defaulth suggested that even once plausible responses by tenants are taken into account DHPs would cover just £1 in every £7 of the impact of housing reforms on tenants.
default&#xa0;
default5.7.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe allocation formula does not reflect 
defaultthe totality of housing impacts. This
default leads to some 
defaultareas facing larger impacts than others.  As a result there is wide variation in how f
defaultar DHPs will meet the ‘residual’
default losses in local areas, after mitigations are taken into account.
default&#xa0;
default5.7.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is the LGA’s view that 
defaultDHP
default should not be seen as the solution to lon
defaultg-term and intractable consequences of the reforms. The Government has presented the additional funding as transitional – in which case the problems it is being used to address should be possible to resolve over time, for example enabling people affected b
defaulty the size criteria to downsize into a smaller property. The LGA is conducting research into the use of DHP by local authorities and will use this as a basis for further discussions with the sector and DWP.
