default6.3
default 
defaultThe pressure on JCP advisers to move peop
defaultle into employment as soon as possible disincentivises providing additional support to vulnerable claimants. The truth is, in developing an employment offer, the majority of JCP advisers, cannot confidently bring together a range of services in an area tha
defaultt an individual may need as part of their journey towards work, even if they are incentivised to do so.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government needs to give councils and their partners in business more influence over work readiness and employment schemes.
default 
defaultCouncils’ wider economi
defaultc development role and local insight means that they can work with employers to forecast
default skills 
defaultthat will be 
defaultneeded
default in the future
default so 
defaultthat 
defaulteducation, further education and 
defaulttraining 
defaultprovision 
defaultproduce
defaults
default more people with skills that are closely matched to what 
defaultemployers in the area need. 
default 
default&#xa0;
default6.4
default 
defaultCouncils are also well placed to co-commission support given their relationship with local public agencies, in depth understanding and proximity to the client base and the services they are most likely to use, and links into 
defaultthe voluntary and community sector
default which can help to build confidence and skills profiles.
default&#xa0;
default6.5
default 
defaultThe outcome and financial benefits of local work and skills support models have been demonstrated in the Whole Place Community Budget Pilots. From these, Ernst and 
defaultYoung have projected annual savings of up to £1.7 billion, the majority of which would be found in DWP budgets.
default&#xa0;
default6.6
default 
defaultThe next letting of Work Programme contracts in 2016 is an ideal opportunity to line up the geography of delivery with the economic development
default actions of councils and their partners through Local Economic Partnerships. Councils should be the commissioners.
default&#xa0;
defaultOxford - Universal Credit face-to-face pilotdefault&#xa0;
defaultOxford identified some common barriers to people entering work, including: lack of child care;
default health issues preventing work; fear of the instability of entering work; lack of skills; debt.
default&#xa0;
defaultThey then tested their understanding of local need with a selection of customers affected by either the social sector size criteria or the housing benefit cap.
default Customer feedback confirmed that these common barriers were experienced by our customers and that most had multiple barriers. They also found that people generally were very keen to engage with the council in overcoming barriers to work. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe council is 
defaultworking with three organisations to support customers – Skills Training UK, JCP and CAB and is moving away from the traditional signposting model to one where the client is directly introduced to the organisation they are referred to. Counci
defaultl staff keep 
defaultin
default contact with the customer after they have received support to identify and responds to any further needs.
default&#xa0;
defaultBy July 2013 Oxford had engaged 180 customers and was working on an on-going basis with 26 of those, of which four had moved into work. A further 16
default cases had been referred to partner organisations - 14 as priority cases; 30 had received discretionary housing payments and all had received housing and/or work related advice. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe councils is also working with Thriving Families (Oxfordshire’s Troubled 
defaultFamilies programme) who are providing some intensive support to customers affected by the social sector size criteria and the housing benefit 
defaultcap. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default7.1
default 
defaultEven at the ‘high’ scenario in our research, which assumes both high levels of inclination and
default motivation in claimants and an optimistic analysis of local employment markets, the scope for households to mitigate reductions in income by moving house or getting a job is relatively limited. And at more plausible estimates, at least four out of every f
defaultive households are likely to need further assistance – with cumulative financial impacts in excess of £1 billion per year.
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default 
defaultCouncils and local partners are clearly best placed to provide advice and guidance at the local level that will enable people to mak
defaulte the best possible decisions for themselves and their families, and to provide targeted support to those who need it to become more stable, motivated or financially literate.  But there is a limit to the amount local partners can achieve while they are co
defaultnstrained by fundamental structural shortcomings in both housing and employment markets and a lack of real influence over jobs and development in their localities.
default&#xa0;
default7.3
default 
defaultThe LGA would like the Government to engage fully with local government on the key challeng
defaultes in their local areas; provide freedom to borrow and spend where there is a clear logic for doing so, and recognise within the design of Universal Credit that the complex barriers faced by some low income families to improving their circumstances are bes
defaultt understood and addressed by local partners at the local level.
